const IDX=[{"title": "Renown", "url": "rules-renown.html", "text": "renown'>Renown\n A turn-based strategy game of empire building, diplomacy, and domain mastery."}, {"title": "Introduction", "url": "rules-introduction.html", "text": "Introduction\nWithin the Realm, Empires expand, specialize, confer, and when diplomacy fails\u2014battle. You will lead your humble Province to greatness. Charter settlements, pursue your economy, and negotiate your way to victory. Will your religion dominate the Realm? Will your economy grow until your wealth is undeniable? Can you build a world wonder? Can you extort your way to victory? Pick your Faction, command your Domain, and pursue your craft in this political grand strategy, where every action you attempt can be endorsed or condemned by your allies and other players.\nGame Synopsis\nRenown is a turn-based political strategy game for 1\u20137 players (3+ preferred) set in a medieval world of competing lords. Each player controls a growing empire \u2014 settlements, armies, and pursuits \u2014 but the game\u2019s central tension isn\u2019t military. It\u2019s political.\nEvery action you want to take has to survive a vote. When you move your army, build a road, or sabotage a rival, every other player at the table gets to spend political influence to support or bury it. The strength of your relationships, the alliances you\u2019ve built, and the favors you\u2019re owed determine whether your plans succeed \u2014 not just your re"}, {"title": "Core Principles", "url": "rules-core-principles.html", "text": "Core Principles\n\nGranted Authority: Any mechanic not explicitly described does not function.\n\n\nSpecial rule priority: More specific rules override general rules.\n\n2.1 Example: Inquisitorial Palace \u2265 Established Cunning &gt; General Cunning Rule.\n\nPublic information: All information is public: resources, domains, Treaties, Armies, Pursuits, and Garrisons are known to all players.\n\n\nOnce Per Turn Effects cannot be used on the same target.\n\n\nInnate + Mastery = Cumulative.\n\n\nA Damaged Pursuit or Infrastructure has neither innate nor mastery effects active.\n\n\nTimer 0: All timers whose initial value is 0 or less resolve immediately.\n\n\nDice rules\n\n8.1. If a Roll is modified beyond 6+, it automatically fails.\n8.2. If a Roll is modified less than 2+, it automatically passes.\n8.3. If modified to 1+ or 7+ but specific results trigger on a 1 or 6, dice must still be rolled for those specific results.\n8.4. You may not re-roll a re-roll or re-roll a success.\n8.5. Effects that occur on a 1 or 6 occur on unmodified rolls of 1 or 6.\n\nRounding down / denomination of 100\n\n9.1. Whenever a gold amount is not divisible by 100, round down to the nearest 100, minimum 0.\n9.2. if your Treasury is negative, "}, {"title": "The Turn", "url": "rules-the-turn.html", "text": "The Turn\nEach turn proceeds through the five phases below in order, then passes the Host and repeats. (See the Turn Outline above for the at-a-glance version.)\nTimers. Many actions set a Timer to a number of turns. Every Empire Phase each active Timer ticks down by 1; when a Timer reaches 0 it resolves and is removed (a Timer set to 0 or less resolves immediately). Each action states its own Timer&#x27;s length \u2014 the named types (Build, Repair, Muster, Siege, Sack, Capture, Convert, Truce) are just labels for what resolves; the rule is the same for all of them."}, {"title": "Empire Phase", "url": "rules-empire-phase.html", "text": "Empire Phase\n\nActivate any unlocked domain standing effects.\nGain seasonal effect \u2014 check the season of this turn and apply its effect.\nIncrement all eligible, active timers in this order: Build, Repair, Truce, Siege, Muster, Sack, Capture Timers\nResolve any timers incremented to 0.\nMay place roads within province.\nHost Resolves Bandit Mechanics:\n\nGrow existing bandit camps according to Era\nIf a camp reaches 25, convert it to an army\nPerform Cunning actions\nPerform move actions\nSpawn new bandit camps (in Spring, from Foster Rebellion, or Uprising)\n\nGain Influence &amp; Envoys:\n\nGain influence based on: Era, innate modifiers (Trade Partners, Alliances, at War, etc.), pursuits, and infrastructure\nGain envoys based on the Era\n\nWinter Phase:\n\nIf Winter, gain tax income equal to your settlements tiers and adjusted by any modifiers.\n\nIncome &amp; Upkeep:\n\nAll players gain pursuit income\nPay army, pursuit, infrastructure, and any additional upkeep\n\nTrade: If there is a host, the host collects trade income and distributes it amongst their trade partners.\nExtort \u2014 Any pursuits or effects that trigger extort are resolved now.\nApply innate Public Order modifiers \u2014 check each Faith/Doubt sourc"}, {"title": "Council Phase", "url": "rules-council-phase.html", "text": "Council Phase\nBefore each player sends personal envoys, there is a council vote on a domain. Each player votes for a domain, clockwise from the starting player; in the case of a tie, the host breaks ties. Then, clockwise from the starting player, each player sends a free envoy and resolves one action of that domain, starting with innate influence equal to their domain standing.\nNote: council envoys\u2019 net influence cannot be lower than 1, regardless of the net influence value."}, {"title": "Envoy Phase", "url": "rules-envoy-phase.html", "text": "envoy-phase'>Envoy Phase\nEnvoy Declaration. Starting with the starting player, all players place their envoys in the Domain tray of their choice.\nThen resolve envoys in order. First, each player who wishes to send a Diplomacy envoy may do so, starting with the starting player; once everyone has had the opportunity, no further Diplomacy envoys may be sent this turn.\nThen players send domain envoys in order: Prowess \u2192 Cunning \u2192 Piety \u2192 Industry, in descending order of magnitude \u2014 the player with the highest Prowess has the first opportunity to send a Prowess envoy, and so on. Once every player has had an opportunity to send an envoy of a domain, no further envoys of that domain may be sent this turn. All remaining envoys must be sent on Industry envoys when given the opportunity.\nTo resolve an envoy \u2014 voting, influence spending, and outcomes \u2014 see Actions &amp; Voting."}, {"title": "Battle Phase", "url": "rules-battle-phase.html", "text": "battle-phase'>Battle Phase\nIf a player performed a Battle or Siege Move action this turn, resolve it now \u2014 see Battles &amp; Sieges for the full procedure."}, {"title": "Rest Phase", "url": "rules-rest-phase.html", "text": "Rest Phase\n\nDiscard any unused envoy &amp; influence tokens.\n\n\nIncrement season by 1.\n\n\nGain Renown.\n\n\nSpend Domain point.\n\n\nChange host \u2014 rotate the host token clockwise to the starting player unless it\u2019s Spring.\n\n\nStart the next Empire Phase.\n"}, {"title": "Seasons", "url": "rules-seasons.html", "text": "Seasons\nThe Realm cycles through four seasons. The current season&#x27;s effect is applied during the Empire Phase, and the Rest Phase advances the season by one.\nSeasonNameEffectWinterFreezingAll Armies gain Speed -1; Sieges do not increment. Tax income collected.SpringPlantingNo Host, Bandit Mechanics, Trade Income, Council Phase, or Diplomacy Actions. Gain +1 Envoy. Bandit Camps Spawn.SummerCampaigningAll Armies gain Speed +2FallHarvestHusbandry Mastery Effects are doubled."}, {"title": "Action Mechanics", "url": "rules-action-mechanics.html", "text": "Action Mechanics\nenvoy'>Sending an Envoy\nEnvoys are the currency of actions: to perform an action you send an envoy during the Envoy Phase. Sending costs 1 envoy, and you must be able to pay the action&#x27;s cost before you send it. Declare the domain and the action \u2014 &quot;I&#x27;d like to send a [Domain] envoy.&quot;\nenvoy'>Resolving an Envoy\nYour envoy begins with influence equal to your innate influence in its domain \u2014 Untested 0, Rising 1, Established 2, Sovereign 3 \u2014 plus any automatic Influence \u00b1X modifiers (these come from your pursuits, infrastructure, and faction, and apply on their own; you never spend influence for them).\nThen, clockwise from the starting player, every other player may respond:\n\nSupport X \u2014 spend X of your influence to raise the envoy&#x27;s net influence.\nOppose X \u2014 spend X of your influence to lower it.\nAbstain \u2014 spend nothing.\n\nYou only spend influence when you Support or Oppose. Abstaining is free, and you may let as much pass unopposed as you like \u2014 though other players may not like that. You cannot vote on your own envoy. Each player may spend up to 1 + their Standing in that domain on a single vote (Untested 1, Rising 2, Established 3, Sovereign"}, {"title": "Influence", "url": "rules-influence.html", "text": "influence'>Influence\nEach turn, gain influence based on the following sources:\nSourceInfluence ChangeNotesEra+1/+2/+3/+4Based on the Current EraTrading Partners+1Per Trading Partner.Alliances+1Per Alliance Member.Infrastructure tier completed+1Per Infrastructure tier fully completed.Cunning Standing+1Flat bonus if you have the Cunning Standing.Fully Mustered Army+1Per active Army of 25 Retinues.Condemned Envoy last turn-1Per Condemned Envoy last turn.At War-3While at War.Other sources+XFrom other effects like Pursuits.\n"}, {"title": "Prowess Actions", "url": "rules-prowess-actions.html", "text": "Prowess Actions\nActionCostRequiresEffect (if passes)EndorsedMoveNone\u2014Move an Army up to its Speed in Territories, then choose: March (move up to 2x Speed, \u22121 Endurance, no other action), Skirmish (end adjacent to a non-allied Army not in a settlement \u2192 Battle, Seize the Initiative +1I Skirmish 1), Lay Siege (end adjacent to an at-war settlement \u2192 Siege), or Muster (within range 3 of your settlements, not within range 1 of a non-ally, with an active Muster Field \u2192 recruit up to combined muster limit; may swap retinues between adjacent allied armies and change equipment). \u2014 Each Army may be the target of only one Move action per turn.; Strained armies do not gain +1 Endurance at the start of next turn.; An Army that Skirmished/Sieged/Mustered cannot act again until that battle/siege/muster timer ends.; An Army that Skirmished gains +1I in the first Skirmish.Perform another Move action (same or different Army).Declare WarNoneRising ProwessChoose a non-allied player you have no NAP or active truce with. Both players are now At War. Trade Agreements between you end. \u2014 If target is in a Defensive Alliance, all members are now at war with you.; If you are in a Military Alliance, all membe"}, {"title": "Cunning Actions", "url": "rules-cunning-actions.html", "text": "Cunning Actions\nActionCostRequiresEffect (if passes)EndorsedIntercept Caravan2000 gold\u2014Choose a player. The next turn they are Host, Extort their Trade Income. \u2014 Affects only a single turn&#x27;s trade income; normal income resumes after.Extort 2000.Foster Rebellion2000 gold\u2014Choose a player. At the next Bandit Mechanic Phase, place a Bandit Camp with 10 retinues in their Outlaw Country. \u2014 If their Outlaw Country has no room, increase it by one territory and spawn there.Extort 2000.Raze2000 gold\u2014Choose another player&#x27;s settlement. Select one active Pursuit, active Infrastructure, or active Build Timer there \u2014 it becomes Damaged; its effects are inactive until Repaired. A damaged Build Timer does not increment until Repaired. \u2014 Wonders have Immune Razed and cannot be targeted.Extort 2000.Destabilize2000 gold\u2014Choose a player. Extort their Tax Income at the beginning of next turn. \u2014 Affects only the next single turn&#x27;s tax income.; Act of War: if a Cunning envoy is Condemned while targeting a NAP partner, they may immediately Declare War on the condemned player.Extort 2000.\nRule: Act of War\nIf a Cunning envoy is condemned while targeting a player with whom you hold a Non-Aggre"}, {"title": "Piety Actions", "url": "rules-piety-actions.html", "text": "Piety Actions\nActionCostRequiresEffect (if passes)EndorsedSpread GospelDoubt 1\u2014All non-allied players gain Doubt 1. All allied players gain Faith 1.Gain Faith 1.Send MissionariesDoubt 1\u2014Choose a target player or alliance. Outside your alliance \u2192 all players in the target alliance gain Doubt 2. Inside your alliance \u2192 all other allied players gain Faith 2.Gain Faith 1.TitheDoubt 1\u2014Choose a player. Extort 10% of their treasury (round down to nearest 100, min 0).Gain Faith 1.ConvertDoubt 1\u2014Choose another player&#x27;s closest non-capital settlement; they must have Public Order \u22125 or lower. Lay Siege using only settlement-type siege modifiers (Wooden Walls, Stone Walls, Citadel, Garrison, Standing Army) and set a Convert Timer. At 0, the settlement joins your empire (see Capture). \u2014 If the target&#x27;s Public Order rises to 1+ before the timer hits 0, the Convert fails and the timer is removed.Gain Faith 1.CrusadeDoubt 1Sovereign PietyDeclare War on a non-ally with no NAP or truce, then immediately perform a Move action with one of your armies. \u2014 While a Crusade is active, neither player may Declare War, Sign/End Treaty, Negotiate, or Demand Tribute against each other.; A player may on"}, {"title": "Industry Actions", "url": "rules-industry-actions.html", "text": "Industry Actions\nActionCostRequiresEffect (if passes)EndorsedBuild2000 gold\u2014Choose an unlocked, available Infrastructure; set a Build Timer equal to its build time. On completion it becomes active in all settlements in your province. \u2014 You must have at least one infrastructure from the prior tier before building the next tier.; Only one active Build Timer at a time.; Wonders are built in your capital and require all other infrastructure active when the Build action is performed.Recoup 2000.Repair2000 gold\u2014Choose a damaged Pursuit or Infrastructure in a settlement you control; set Repair Timer 2. At 0, choose: Restore (reactivate with all effects) or Demolish (remove it, freeing the ward).Recoup 2000.Pursue2000 gold\u2014Choose an inactive settlement ward you control. Select a Pursuit whose prerequisites you meet; set a Build Timer equal to its build time (usually 1). On completion, place the Pursuit; innate effects activate immediately, mastery if all mastery reqs met. \u2014 You may have only 2 Monument pursuits across your empire.; Power and unique pursuits have Build Timer +1; Monuments +2; all others Build Timer 1.Recoup 2000.Charter2000 gold\u2014Choose: Charter a new Village (uncontrolled o"}, {"title": "Diplomacy Actions", "url": "rules-diplomacy-actions.html", "text": "diplomacy-actions'>Diplomacy Actions\nActionCostRequiresEffect (if passes)EndorsedSign TreatyNone\u2014Ask players to agree; choose one and both sign one of: Peace Treaty (end war, truce timer 5), Trade Agreement (begin trading next turn), Non-Aggression Pact (no Declare War; ending it via End Treaty gives both truce timer 5), or Alliance (join/form/invite to Defensive or Military Alliance). \u2014 Acting on behalf of an alliance, End Treaty requires all allies to agree.; A player may not be in more than one alliance (exception: Masters of Duplicity).Perform a Diplomacy action.NegotiateNone\u2014Propose terms to a target; they agree or refuse. Terms may include gold, settlement ownership, territory, treaty sign/end, or promises (non-binding). \u2014 Unfulfilled promises let the affected player Declare War on the promiser.; Also used (automatically, no envoy) to resolve Demand Tribute and siege surrenders.Perform a Diplomacy action.End TreatyNone\u2014Choose a target with an active treaty signed with you; that treaty is removed. Does not require the target to agree.Perform a Diplomacy action.\n"}, {"title": "Domains & Standings", "url": "rules-domains-standings.html", "text": "Domains &amp; Standings\ndomain-standings'>Domain Standings\n \tDomains are the identity of your character in Renown. As you gain Renown each turn, you\u2019ll gain access to a Domain point, which you can spend in any of the four Domains. Every time you spend a Domain point, you increase your Domain value by 1. When your Domain value becomes three, you become Rising in that Domain, allowing you spend an additional influence on another player\u2019s envoy of that domain, and your envoys gain influence +1. You also unlock a unique effect. This continues when you have a domain value of six, causing you to become Established in that domain, and Sovereign when your reach a domain value of ten.\nEach standing you gain in a domain makes you harder to stop in that area and allows you stop others more easily. In addition, you gain a unique effect at each standing that makes it easier to pursue the objectives of that domain.\n Domain Identities &amp; Traits\nDomainUntestedRising (3)Established (6)Sovereign (10)Industry\u2014Trade Secrets: Perform endorsed Pursuit.Grand Architect: May have an additional City. Perform endorsed Charter.Titan of Industry: Your capital may be chartered to a Metropolis. Perform endors"}, {"title": "Diplomacy & Treaties", "url": "rules-diplomacy-treaties.html", "text": "diplomacy-treaties'>Diplomacy &amp; Treaties\nTreaties &amp; Alliances\nTreatySigned ViaEraEffectPeace TreatySign TreatyAnyEnds war between the two players; sets Truce Timer 5.Trade AgreementSign TreatyAnyBegin trading (Trade Income flows from next turn). Requires bordering + active Dirt Road.Non-Aggression PactSign TreatyAnyNeither player may Declare War on the other. Ending it via End Treaty gives both a Truce Timer 5.Military AllianceSign TreatyEminenceMutual offensive pact: if a member Declares War, all members Declare War on the target next turn (and send 1 fewer envoy).Defensive AllianceSign TreatyZenithMutual defense: attacking one member puts all members at war with the attacker.\n Alliance Rules:\nNew alliance members are added by unanimous agreement.A player cannot be in more than one alliance at a time (exception: Masters of Duplicity).An alliance may cast out a member via End Treaty if all others agree.\nVassalization\nTo vassalize a player:\n\nControl that player\u2019s capital settlement and the player has no other settlements or armies under it\u2019s control.\n\n\nAt the end of the Rest Phase, return all settlements you control that were chartered by that player to that player. You beco"}, {"title": "Settlements", "url": "rules-settlements.html", "text": "Settlements\nSettlements are the primary vehicle of your Empire. Settlements are separated into tiers: villages, towns, cities, and a metropolis. Each tier provides tax income each turn, settlement wards that can be filled by a pursuit, and a per-turn muster limit of retinues. The exact values per tier are below:\nSettlementTaxMusterWardsReachBuildSea VariantNotesHamlet00311\u2014Husbandry pursuits only; exactly range 2 from capital; may always pursue Arable LandVillage20005111\u2014Town400010222Sea TownCity600025333PortMetropolis1000025445\u2014Capital only, requires Sovereign Industry (Titan of Industry)\nSettlement Wards\nSettlements contain 1 settlement ward for each tier of settlement your settlement is. Villages have 1 central hub, which all other settlement wards must be adjacent (range 1), towns have 2 settlement wards, cities have 3, and a metropolis can have 4. The only exception is a hamlet, which is a village that can only contain husbandry pursuits, but can contains 3 settlement wards.\nChartering Settlements\nWhen chartering new settlements, you must place them at least range 4 from all other settlements, and range 2 from any outlaw country. In addition, you cannot charter settlements on "}, {"title": "Infrastructure", "url": "rules-infrastructure.html", "text": "Infrastructure\n \tInfrastructure is the infrastructure of your settlements. Each infrastructure you have active provides a effect that affects your entire empire and settlements.\n \tFor example, Wooden walls protect all settlements from cunning envoys, and Cathedrals increase your innate Faith by 1 each turn, regardless of how many settlements you have.\n \tInfrastructure is broken into 5 different tiers that are arranged in ascending tiers. First, there\u2019s primitive infrastructure, that builds the basic blocks of your empire. Next, there\u2019s developed infrastructure, which expands and replaces some primitive infrastructure. Then, there\u2019s sophisticated infrastructure, which allows for more powerful effects and helps unlock unique monument pursuits. Only a single infrastructure can have an active build timer concurrently.\n \tLastly, there\u2019s world wonders. Wonders are unique infrastructure that each can only be built once per game, once all other infrastructure is built and active in your empire. These are Edict satisfying buildings that provide very powerful effects. Wonders exist inside your capital and cannot be razed or damaged.\nThe full list of infrastructure \u2014 their tiers, build times,"}, {"title": "Territory & Terrain", "url": "rules-territory-terrain.html", "text": "territory-terrain'>Territory &amp; Terrain\nTerritory is the smallest unit of land. To move from one territory to another, you move range 1. To be within a territory, you are range 0; adjacent, range 1; next to, range 2.\n \tTerritories have modifiers based on the type of hex they are (grassland, forest, tundra, wetlands, water, &amp; mountain), and can either be uncontrolled, contested, or controlled. Territory begins as uncontrolled. By chartering settlements, you can control territories. All settlements have a reach X, adding all territory to your province within the range of your settlements equal to your reach characteristic. However, if another player\u2019s settlement reach is within reach of any territory you control, it is contested.\n \tTo border another player, your reach must be within or adjacent to another player\u2019s reach.\nTerrainEffectRaw MaterialsGrassland\u2014Arable Land, ApiaryWetlandsSpeed -1Peat Bog, ForestryTundragain StrainedQuarry, Salt WorksMountainsImpassableMineWaterMust end move after passing over 1 Water Territory (must end on land)FishmongeryForestSpeed -1Forestry, ApiaryHillGains Seize the Initiative. Where Settlements can be chartered.\u2014"}, {"title": "Public Order", "url": "rules-public-order.html", "text": "Public Order\nFaith and Doubt adjust your Public Order the moment they are generated \u2014 each Faith raises it by 1, each Doubt lowers it by 1, applied immediately. Public Order is capped between \u22125 and 10, and the effects of your current band (below) are always active at your current value.\nFirst Doubt of the turn. Some effects (e.g. Reliquary, Episcopal Court) reduce the first Doubt you gain each turn, from any source. Because Doubt now applies immediately, this is whichever Doubt lands first in the turn \u2014 usually your innate modifiers in the Empire Phase, but it can be an opponent&#x27;s action if that resolves first. Track whether you have taken Doubt yet this turn; the marker resets at the start of each Empire Phase, before innate modifiers are applied.\nYour innate Public Order modifiers (below) are checked once each turn during the Empire Phase and applied like any other Faith/Doubt.\nPOStateEffect-5UprisingBandit Camp spawns in your Outlaw Country-4Recession-1000 Tax Income per Settlement-3AimlessSpeed -1-2Indecisive-1 Influence-1WaveringNo effect0NeutralNo effect1FocusedNo effect2Confident+1 Influence3MotivatedSpeed +14Economic BoomTax income +500 per settlement5EurekaActivate 1"}, {"title": "Treasury & Upkeep", "url": "rules-treasury-upkeep.html", "text": "Treasury &amp; Upkeep\nYour Treasury is the gold you control. Each Empire Phase you gain your Revenue (tax, trade, and pursuit income) and pay your Upkeep (armies, pursuits, and infrastructure); the net lands in your Treasury. Costs you pay during the turn come out of the same Treasury.\nTracking tip: keep three small piles \u2014 Treasury, Revenue, Upkeep. When you build something with income or upkeep, add it to the matching pile; when it&#x27;s damaged or an army loses retinues, subtract it. Then each turn it&#x27;s just Treasury + Revenue \u2212 Upkeep, with no recounting.\nInsolvency &amp; Bankruptcy\n&gt; This is an exception path \u2014 skip it until it happens.\nYou go Insolvent the moment your Treasury can&#x27;t cover a cost in full (at Upkeep, when paying for an action, or when an effect drains your gold). Pay what you can, then cut until the books balance, in this order:\n\nDisband retinues, one at a time, cheapest-upkeep first, until your armies are gone.\nSet buildings inactive, highest-tier first (Monuments, then Power pursuits, then other non-natural pursuits).\n\nAn inactive pursuit gives no innate or mastery effect, and anything that needed it as a prerequisite loses its mastery. An inact"}, {"title": "Trade & Income", "url": "rules-trade-income.html", "text": "Trade &amp; Income\nWho Can Trade &amp; Income\n Who Can Trade: players need to border each other, have active dirt road infrastructure, and have a signed trade agreement to participate in trade.\nCraft X: Craft are pursuits that count towards how much income is generated from your trade agreements. The types are any effect that gives Craft +X.\nTrade Income: For each active trade agreement, both players gain gold equal to 100 \u00d7 the host\u2019s Craft X.\nWhen Income Flows:\n\nWhen you sign a trade agreement: The player who did not perform the sign treaty action gets trade income next time they are host. Afterwards, both get trade income each turn.\nWhen you end a trade agreement: The player who ended the treaty gets trade income next time they are host, then trading ceases.\n\nIncome Types\nIncome Types:\n\nTaxes: At start of each round, gain tax income equal to your settlement total, after modifiers.\nTrade: See above.\nPursuits: Gain innate and active mastery effect income at the start of income phase.\n"}, {"title": "Armies", "url": "rules-armies.html", "text": "Armies\nArmies Overview\nArmies are a collection of retinues that exist on the realm. Armies are the target of move actions. Armies consist of up to 25 retinues with up to a single piece of equipment from each type (armor, weapons, shields).\n \tArmies cost upkeep that must be spent in the empire phase. To calculate your upkeep for your army, multiply the count of retinues by their retinue type cost, subtracted by any upkeep modifiers.\n \tNote: For example, Net Upkeep = Retinue Count * (Retinue Cost - Upkeep Modifiers)\nIf an has been engaged in a battle or lay siege action started by another player\u2019s army, both armies cannot be the target of any actions until the battle or lay siege has been resolved.\nRecruiting an Army\nWhen you perform a muster action, if you do not have the maximum amount of armies you are allowed, you may place an army is within (range 0) a settlement you control that is not being sieged by another player. When you do, you may muster an amount of retinues according to the muster limit of the settlement, pay the appropriate cost according to the type of retinue you are eligible to purchase, select their equipment based on the available equipment you have to choose fro"}, {"title": "Battle Phase", "url": "rules-battle-phase.html", "text": "battle-phase'>Battle Phase\nbattle'>Begin Battle\nskirmish'>Begin Skirmish\n\nDeclare army \u2014 Declare which army will skirmish (if more than 1 is adjacent to either army in battle).\n\n\nChoose a tactic \u2014 Place a face-down tactic and reveal when the other player has done so too.\n\n\nDeclare equipment (if you have a tiltyard or one shot weapon)\n\n\nResolve tactic modifier \u2014 After tactics have been revealed, modify your initiative and any other modifiers from tactics and your weapon profile.\n\nbattle-resolves'>How a Battle Resolves\nA Battle is fought as a series of Skirmishes, run through the steps below until one side is wiped out, Routs, or successfully Falls Back. Full keyword detail is in the Compendium glossary.\nbattle-seize-the-initiative'>Begin the Battle \u2014 Seize the Initiative\nEach player rolls one D6 (+1 if they won their last Battle), re-rolling ties. The higher roller Seizes the Initiative: they are the Attacker this Battle and gain +1 Initiative in the first Skirmish; their opponent is the Defender.\nskirmish-steps'>The Skirmish Steps\nForm the line. Each side places up to 10 retinues in its front line \u2014 one Strike die each \u2014 and may keep up to 5 in reserve to replace losses as they fal"}, {"title": "Siege Warfare", "url": "rules-siege-warfare.html", "text": "siege-warfare'>Siege Warfare\n\nIf you lay siege during the envoy Phase, track the relevant siege timer(s).\nWhen a siege timer reaches 0, resolve the siege before Rest Phase (negotiate \u2192 battle if needed \u2192 capture/sack).\nFor full Siege rules, see warfare \u2192 siege warfare.\n\nsiege'>Beginning a Siege\n\nEnd a move army action to become adjacent to an another player\u2019s settlement you\u2019re at war with.\n\n\nYour army must remain there for the siege timer and cannot take other actions.\n\n\nIf attacked while sieging \u2014 if you fallback or use defensive formation, the siege is broken and the siege timer is removed from play.\n\n\nSettlements being besieged: cannot count pursuits for the purposes of Craft X; armies gain blocked except to sally forth; timers targeting the settlement do not increment; industry actions cannot target it.\n\nsiege'>Resolving a Siege\nWhen a Siege Timer reaches 0:\n\nIf not yet negotiated, negotiate now.\n\n\nIf negotiate fails and there\u2019s an army or garrison inside, battle in Battle Phase.\n\n\nIf the besieging player wins or there is no eligible army or garrison:\n\n\nCapture: capture timer 1. When resolved, the settlement is under your control: the settlement receive your active infrastructu"}, {"title": "Bandits", "url": "rules-bandits.html", "text": "Bandits\nOutlaw Country\nOutlaw Country is a collection of territory in your starting settlement region that you cannot control. At the beginning of the game, you\u2019ll demarcate 3 territories in your starting settlement region, all no more than range 1 of at least 1 other Outlaw Country territory and at least range 2 from any settlement.\n If this is not possible, place them range 2 from your capital settlement.\nbandit-camps'>Spawning Bandit Camps\nAt the beginning of Bandit Mechanic Phase in Spring: Place a bandit camp with 5 Bandits (retinues) in each player\u2019s Outlaw Country.\n Note: if your outlaw country is selected to receive another bandit camp, but there is no room to place one, increase your outlaw country territory by one, and spawn the bandit camp there.\nbandit-camps'>Growing Bandit Camps\nA bandit camp becomes a bandit army when it reaches 25 Retinues.\nbandit-armaments-by-era'>Bandit Armaments by Era\nEraRetinues Gained per TurnFounding1Ascension2Eminence5Zenith10\nbandit-info'>Bandit Info\nBandits share the same Renown level as players. Bandit Domain value is determined by the size of it\u2019s Bandit Camp:\n\n+1 Cunning and +1 Prowess for every multiple of 5 Bandits in the camp(e.g., 30"}, {"title": "Quarry", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#quarry", "text": "Quarry Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Salt Works", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#salt-works", "text": "Salt Works Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Apiary", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#apiary", "text": "Apiary Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Peat Bog", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#peat-bog", "text": "Peat Bog Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Forestry", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#forestry", "text": "Forestry Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Fishmongery", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#fishmongery", "text": "Fishmongery Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Mine", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#mine", "text": "Mine Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Arable Land", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#arable-land", "text": "Arable Land Raw Materials +300, **Natural**; Craft +1 "}, {"title": "Common Land", "url": "type-raw-materials.html#common-land", "text": "Common Land Raw Materials +500, **Natural**, **Doubt +1** "}, {"title": "Herb Garden", "url": "type-husbandry.html#herb-garden", "text": "Herb Garden Husbandry +200, **Natural** Craft +1"}, {"title": "Animal Husbandry", "url": "type-husbandry.html#animal-husbandry", "text": "Animal Husbandry Husbandry +100, **Natural** +300"}, {"title": "Saddlery", "url": "type-husbandry.html#saddlery", "text": "Saddlery Husbandry +200, **Natural** **Upkeep -200**; Speed +1"}, {"title": "Vineyard", "url": "type-husbandry.html#vineyard", "text": "Vineyard Husbandry **Natural** +600 in **Fall**"}, {"title": "Orchard", "url": "type-husbandry.html#orchard", "text": "Orchard Husbandry **Natural** +400 in **Fall**"}, {"title": "Secret Cellar", "url": "type-energy.html#secret-cellar", "text": "Secret Cellar Energy \u2014 Passed Cunning actions **Recoup 500 Gold**"}, {"title": "Pilgrimage Site", "url": "type-energy.html#pilgrimage-site", "text": "Pilgrimage Site Energy **Extort 200** every player without a Pilgrimage Site **Doubt +1** to all other players without a Pilgrimage Site"}, {"title": "Beacon Towers", "url": "type-energy.html#beacon-towers", "text": "Beacon Towers Energy \u2014 Whenever a non-allied Army ends a Move action within Province, you may immediately perform a Move action"}, {"title": "Charcoal Burner", "url": "type-energy.html#charcoal-burner", "text": "Charcoal Burner Energy +400 "}, {"title": "Mill", "url": "type-energy.html#mill", "text": "Mill Energy +300 "}, {"title": "Kiln", "url": "type-energy.html#kiln", "text": "Kiln Energy +300 "}, {"title": "Burgages", "url": "type-energy.html#burgages", "text": "Burgages Energy +200 **Faith +1**"}, {"title": "Carpentry", "url": "type-craft.html#carpentry", "text": "Carpentry Craft **Build Timer \u22121** +100; Craft+1"}, {"title": "Alchemy", "url": "type-craft.html#alchemy", "text": "Alchemy Craft +100 +200; Craft+1"}, {"title": "Masonry", "url": "type-craft.html#masonry", "text": "Masonry Craft **Build Timer \u22121** +100; Craft+1"}, {"title": "Butchery", "url": "type-craft.html#butchery", "text": "Butchery Craft +300 **Upkeep -200**; Craft+1"}, {"title": "Bakery", "url": "type-craft.html#bakery", "text": "Bakery Craft +300; Faith +1 +100; Craft +2"}, {"title": "Weavery", "url": "type-craft.html#weavery", "text": "Weavery Craft +300 +300; Craft +2"}, {"title": "Fletchery", "url": "type-craft.html#fletchery", "text": "Fletchery Craft Unlocks **Ranged Weapons** **Upkeep -200**"}, {"title": "Chandlery", "url": "type-craft.html#chandlery", "text": "Chandlery Craft +200 **Influence \u22121** to Cunning actions targeting you; Craft +1"}, {"title": "Tannery", "url": "type-craft.html#tannery", "text": "Tannery Craft Unlocks **Cast** armor & shield. **Upkeep -200**; Craft +1"}, {"title": "Joinery", "url": "type-craft.html#joinery", "text": "Joinery Craft +200, unlocks **Shields** **Upkeep -200**"}, {"title": "Furnace", "url": "type-craft.html#furnace", "text": "Furnace Craft Unlocks **Cast Weapons** +200"}, {"title": "Blacksmith", "url": "type-craft.html#blacksmith", "text": "Blacksmith Craft +200; Craft +1 Unlocks **Wrought** Tier"}, {"title": "Jewelry Foundry", "url": "type-craft.html#jewelry-foundry", "text": "Jewelry Foundry Craft +200; Craft +2 +500; **Influence +2** to Cunning Envoys targeting this player"}, {"title": "Armory", "url": "type-craft.html#armory", "text": "Armory Craft **Unlock Wrought** armor & shield **Upkeep -200**; Craft +1"}, {"title": "Master Workshop", "url": "type-craft.html#master-workshop", "text": "Master Workshop Craft **Upkeep -200**; Craft +1 Add **Serrated** to Weapons"}, {"title": "Gilded Foundry", "url": "type-craft.html#gilded-foundry", "text": "Gilded Foundry Craft Unlock **Forged** armor and shield. Tempered: Your to Save modifier cannot be reduced beyond 6+; Craft +1"}, {"title": "Smokehouse", "url": "type-craft.html#smokehouse", "text": "Smokehouse Craft +300; Craft +1 **Upkeep -200**"}, {"title": "Workyard", "url": "type-craft.html#workyard", "text": "Workyard Craft **Doubt +1**, +400 +400"}, {"title": "Storehouse", "url": "type-craft.html#storehouse", "text": "Storehouse Craft **Doubt +2**, +600 **Build Timer \u22122**"}, {"title": "Meadery", "url": "type-craft.html#meadery", "text": "Meadery Craft **Faith +1**, +300 +200,**Speed +1** in **Winter**"}, {"title": "Winery", "url": "type-craft.html#winery", "text": "Winery Craft +400 Craft +3"}, {"title": "Cidery", "url": "type-craft.html#cidery", "text": "Cidery Craft **Faith +1**, +300 +300; Craft +1"}, {"title": "Market Square", "url": "type-craft.html#market-square", "text": "Market Square Craft Craft +2 +400"}, {"title": "Inn", "url": "type-craft.html#inn", "text": "Inn Craft **Faith +1** for trading partners with Craft 3+ **Faith +1**"}, {"title": "Spice Merchant", "url": "type-craft.html#spice-merchant", "text": "Spice Merchant Craft +300; Influence +1 to Cunning Envoys targeting you +500; Craft +2"}, {"title": "Harbor", "url": "type-craft.html#harbor", "text": "Harbor Craft +300; Craft +2 **Extort 200** per **player** without **Harbor**"}, {"title": "Merchant Quarter", "url": "type-craft.html#merchant-quarter", "text": "Merchant Quarter Craft +500 Trade Partners gain Craft +2"}, {"title": "Census Hall", "url": "type-craft.html#census-hall", "text": "Census Hall Craft **Doubt +1**; +200 +500"}, {"title": "Caravanery", "url": "type-craft.html#caravanery", "text": "Caravanery Craft **Influence -1** to **Intercept Caravan actions** targeting your **settlements** **Craft +2**; **Speed -2** to non-allied players in your Province."}, {"title": "Shipyard", "url": "type-craft.html#shipyard", "text": "Shipyard Craft Craft +1 Craft +2; Water Territory treated as Grassland for movement"}, {"title": "Money Lending", "url": "type-power.html#money-lending", "text": "Money Lending Power **Extort 500** May loan money to Trade Partners at 100 per 1000/turn interest(minimum 100); on Default: Perform **Demand Tribute**"}, {"title": "Monastery", "url": "type-power.html#monastery", "text": "Monastery Power **Influence \u22121** to Piety actions targeting you Other players cannot Oppose your Piety Envoys"}, {"title": "Hospitaller", "url": "type-power.html#hospitaller", "text": "Hospitaller Power **Recover** improved by +1 gain Enduring: Your recovers cannot be reduced beyond a 6+ while Fatigued."}, {"title": "University", "url": "type-power.html#university", "text": "University Power May spend one additional **Influence** per Support or Oppose +1 **Influence** per Domain you are Rising"}, {"title": "College of Engineering", "url": "type-power.html#college-of-engineering", "text": "College of Engineering Power No Upkeep on **Sophisticated Infrastructure** **Build Timer \u22122**"}, {"title": "Forgery Workshop", "url": "type-power.html#forgery-workshop", "text": "Forgery Workshop Power **Extort 200** anytime a player Opposes an Envoy of yours Once/turn: attempt another Cunning Envoy targeting a different player if your Cunning Envoy Failed"}, {"title": "Levy Hall", "url": "type-power.html#levy-hall", "text": "Levy Hall Power **Upkeep -200** **Upkeep -300**"}, {"title": "Siege Works", "url": "type-power.html#siege-works", "text": "Siege Works Power **Siege Timer \u22121** **Siege Timer \u22121**; Sieges Increment in **Winter**"}, {"title": "Siege Camp", "url": "type-power.html#siege-camp", "text": "Siege Camp Power **Siege Timer \u22121** Armies gain **Immune Strained** during Lay Siege"}, {"title": "Citadel", "url": "type-power.html#citadel", "text": "Citadel Power **Siege Timer +1** **Siege Timer +1**, Controlled Settlements gain **Reach +1**"}, {"title": "War College", "url": "type-power.html#war-college", "text": "War College Power Gain **+2 Influence** while At War Unlocks **Sergeants** for Muster"}, {"title": "Forge", "url": "type-power.html#forge", "text": "Forge Power Craft +1 Unlocks **Forged** Tier"}, {"title": "Tiltyard", "url": "type-power.html#tiltyard", "text": "Tiltyard Power Armies may be Equipped with a second weapon (a Ranged and a Melee Weapon); the army gains **Unwieldy** Armies gain **Immune Unwieldy**, and may instead equip two of the same 1H Melee Weapon to gain **Dual Wield**, **2H** & **Florentine**: May Parry on a natural 6 while Fatigued."}, {"title": "Cipher Chamber", "url": "type-power.html#cipher-chamber", "text": "Cipher Chamber Power Once/turn when a player Sends an Envoy: that player must declare the specific Action they would Perform if the Envoy Passes (including sub-Actions). If it Passes, they must Perform that declared Action. Once/turn: select any active **Timer** you did not select last turn; increase it by 2."}, {"title": "Stable", "url": "type-civic.html#stable", "text": "Stable Civic **Speed +1** **Speed +1**; Unlocks Cavalry Weapons"}, {"title": "Coliseum", "url": "type-civic.html#coliseum", "text": "Coliseum Civic **Faith +1** while at War Unlocks **Man-at-Arms** for **Muster**"}, {"title": "Interrogation Chambers", "url": "type-civic.html#interrogation-chambers", "text": "Interrogation Chambers Civic  Cunning actions targetting this player that cause Doubt are reduced by 1, to a minimum of 0."}, {"title": "Abbey", "url": "type-civic.html#abbey", "text": "Abbey Civic Once/turn: **Influence +1** another player's Piety Envoy Morale +1."}, {"title": "Reliquary", "url": "type-civic.html#reliquary", "text": "Reliquary Civic  First **Doubt** per turn reduced by 1 (min 0)"}, {"title": "Bell Tower", "url": "type-civic.html#bell-tower", "text": "Bell Tower Civic **+1 Influence**/turn **Influence +1** to Piety actions"}, {"title": "Execution Dock", "url": "type-civic.html#execution-dock", "text": "Execution Dock Civic **Influence -1** to **Foster Rebellion actions** targeting your **settlements** **Players** who **target** you or your **settlements** with **actions** that cause **doubt** gain **Doubt +1**"}, {"title": "Jester's Court", "url": "type-civic.html#jester-s-court", "text": "Jester's Court Civic First **Oppose** on your Envoy: reduce by 1 Second **Oppose** on your Envoy: reduce by 1"}, {"title": "Embassy", "url": "type-civic.html#embassy", "text": "Embassy Civic **Influence +1** to Diplomacy Envoys Players that perform a Diplomacy action targetting you may perform another Displomacy action targetting you."}, {"title": "Granary", "url": "type-civic.html#granary", "text": "Granary Civic Upkeep -200 Armies and Garrisons gain **Endurance** while Besieged"}, {"title": "Academy", "url": "type-civic.html#academy", "text": "Academy Civic **Influence +1** to Council Envoys **Influence +1** to non-Council Envoys"}, {"title": "Courtyard", "url": "type-civic.html#courtyard", "text": "Courtyard Civic Craft +1 **Faith +1**"}, {"title": "Episcopal Court", "url": "type-civic.html#episcopal-court", "text": "Episcopal Court Civic **Faith +1** Reduce the first instance of Doubt at start of turn by 1, min 0."}, {"title": "Conditioning Field", "url": "type-civic.html#conditioning-field", "text": "Conditioning Field Civic **Faith +1** while not at War Armies gain **Nimble**"}, {"title": "Grand Tournament", "url": "type-civic.html#grand-tournament", "text": "Grand Tournament Civic **Faith +1** 3x/turn: exchange 500 gold for **1 Influence**; Armies gain **Riposte**"}, {"title": "Apothecary", "url": "type-civic.html#apothecary", "text": "Apothecary Civic +300 Gain Recover 6, or improve Recover by +1."}, {"title": "Infirmary", "url": "type-civic.html#infirmary", "text": "Infirmary Civic +200 Improve Recover by +1"}, {"title": "Supply Depot", "url": "type-civic.html#supply-depot", "text": "Supply Depot Civic **Craft +2** May **Muster** an Army in a Settlement under Siege and increment Muster Timers."}, {"title": "Artisan Workshop", "url": "type-civic.html#artisan-workshop", "text": "Artisan Workshop Civic +400 +200, **Faith +1**"}, {"title": "Trade Guild", "url": "type-civic.html#trade-guild", "text": "Trade Guild Civic No Upkeep on **Primitive Infrastructure** No Upkeep on **Developed Infrastructure**"}, {"title": "Court Artists", "url": "type-civic.html#court-artists", "text": "Court Artists Civic **Extort 500**; **Faith +1** **Extort 500**; Target of Extort gains **Faith +1**"}, {"title": "Courier Network", "url": "type-civic.html#courier-network", "text": "Courier Network Civic Once/turn: **Influence \u22121** on Target Envoy Once/turn: successfully Performed Personal Envoy can be Performed next turn; send 1 fewer Envoys next turn"}, {"title": "Toll House", "url": "type-civic.html#toll-house", "text": "Toll House Civic Once/turn when an Army ends a Move action within Province: Perform a Diplomacy action targeting that army's player **Extort 500** when non-Allied Army ends a Move action within Province"}, {"title": "Smuggler's Nook", "url": "type-secrecy.html#smuggler-s-nook", "text": "Smuggler's Nook Secrecy gain Immune Local Unrest (-1PO per Bandit Camp) Bandit Camps in your Outlaw Country don't target you and target other players instead randomly."}, {"title": "Black Market", "url": "type-secrecy.html#black-market", "text": "Black Market Secrecy When another player **Extorts** gold from any source: **Extort 200** per 1000 (minimum 100) from that player at the end of that resolution. When another player **Recoups** gold from any source: **Extort 200** per 1000 (minimum 100) from that player at the end of that resolution."}, {"title": "Toxicarium", "url": "type-secrecy.html#toxicarium", "text": "Toxicarium Secrecy Weapons gain **Poison** All Endorsed Cunning actions give an additional **Doubt +1** to Target"}, {"title": "Forgotten Catacombs", "url": "type-secrecy.html#forgotten-catacombs", "text": "Forgotten Catacombs Secrecy Whenever you are the target of **Extort**, reduce the Extort amount by 100 (min 100). Cunning actions against you cannot be **Endorsed**"}, {"title": "Royal Pavilion", "url": "type-monument.html#royal-pavilion", "text": "Royal Pavilion Monument Armies gain **Immune Strained** Armies gain **Drilled**"}, {"title": "Imperial Palace", "url": "type-monument.html#imperial-palace", "text": "Imperial Palace Monument Gain **Immune Border Tension & Invasion** Non-Military Alliance players that border you gain **Doubt +2**"}, {"title": "Ministry of Military Strategy", "url": "type-monument.html#ministry-of-military-strategy", "text": "Ministry of Military Strategy Monument Always gains **Seize the Initiative**, and your opponent doesn't. gain Immune Tactic -1 to Strike Gain +1I & max initiative is 3; Deadly, & Cleave also trigger Focused Strikes on a natural 5."}, {"title": "Thieves' Guild", "url": "type-monument.html#thieves-guild", "text": "Thieves' Guild Monument Whenever another player performs a Cunning action, you may recoup 1000 gold **Extort 25%** of Trade Income from players who don't trade with you"}, {"title": "Senate Hall", "url": "type-monument.html#senate-hall", "text": "Senate Hall Monument **Faith +1**, gain **+1 Influence** per other player per Turn Once/turn: Before players Support or Oppose, you may auto-**Condemn** an At War Envoy OR auto-**Endorse** an Ally's Envoy"}, {"title": "Inquisitorial Palace", "url": "type-monument.html#inquisitorial-palace", "text": "Inquisitorial Palace Monument **Doubt +1**; Unlocks **Grand Vizier** which uses your **Public Order** instead of your **Cunning** value. You may use your **Piety Value** as **Cunning Value** for **Grand Vizier**."}, {"title": "Preceptory of the Knight's Templar", "url": "type-monument.html#preceptory-of-the-knight-s-templar", "text": "Preceptory of the Knight's Templar Monument Armies gain **Zealous**: Automatically pass the first Panic Check of every Battle. Unlocks **Knight's Templar** for Muster"}, {"title": "Manor House", "url": "type-monument.html#manor-house", "text": "Manor House Monument Gain +100 gold for each active natural specialization. Gain +100 gold for each active energy specialization."}, {"title": "Aristocratic Court", "url": "type-monument.html#aristocratic-court", "text": "Aristocratic Court Monument **Doubt +1** per player who earns more Income than you each turn in the Income step. Your Vote counts as 2 votes toward Domain selection during the Council Phase."}, {"title": "Studium Generale", "url": "type-monument.html#studium-generale", "text": "Studium Generale Monument +1 **Influence** per **Established** Standing May gain one **Sovereign Domain** effect without spending the Domain Points"}, {"title": "Advanced Blast Furnace", "url": "type-monument.html#advanced-blast-furnace", "text": "Advanced Blast Furnace Monument **Upkeep -500** **Crafted** Tier Unlocked; Craft +2"}, {"title": "Outrider Intercept Post", "url": "type-monument.html#outrider-intercept-post", "text": "Outrider Intercept Post Monument In the first Skirmish of every Battle, your opponent plays their Tactic Card face up before you select your own. Every Skirmish, you may force your opponent to reveal their Tactic Card they selected before you select your own."}, {"title": "Turn Sequence", "url": "turn-sequence.html", "text": "turn sequence empire council envoy battle rest phase order of play"}, {"title": "Dirt Roads", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Dirt Roads infrastructure Can Trade; place Dirt Road Territories in Province; ignore Terrain Speed Modifiers"}, {"title": "Hitching Post", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Hitching Post infrastructure Craft +1"}, {"title": "Muster Field", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Muster Field infrastructure Can Muster"}, {"title": "Wooden Walls", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Wooden Walls infrastructure **Influence -1** to **Raze actions** targeting your **settlements**"}, {"title": "Stone Roads", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Stone Roads infrastructure Ignore Terrain Speed Modifiers; if you start turn on Stone Road gain Speed +2; replaces Dirt Roads"}, {"title": "Town Hall", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Town Hall infrastructure +1 Influence per turn"}, {"title": "Bridges", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Bridges infrastructure Armies cross Water Territory at full movement; Stone Roads may be built over Water"}, {"title": "Garrison", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Garrison infrastructure Local Armies form (10/15/25 by Settlement size). All Garrisons share Equipment. Cannot be targeted; may Sally Forth."}, {"title": "Stone Walls", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Stone Walls infrastructure **Influence -1** to **Destabilize actions** targeting your **settlements**"}, {"title": "Keep", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Keep infrastructure May Muster from Garrison in addition to normal Muster Limits. If so set Garrison to 0 and Muster Timer 1. Garrison returns to full when resolved."}, {"title": "Cathedral", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Cathedral infrastructure Faith +1"}, {"title": "Library", "url": "infrastructure-ref.html", "text": "Library infrastructure Influence +1 to Council Envoys"}, {"title": "Colossus", "url": "wonders-ref.html", "text": "Colossus wonder You may **support** your own **prowess envoys** before other **players vote**. **Armies** move **Speed +2** **Siege Timer -2** gain **Immune Blunder**."}, {"title": "The Grand Exchange", "url": "wonders-ref.html", "text": "The Grand Exchange wonder Whenever you generate **Trade Income** you generate **twice as much** for yourself."}, {"title": "The Great Basilica", "url": "wonders-ref.html", "text": "The Great Basilica wonder If your **Public Order** would ever be less than 5 set it to 5 instead. Your **Settlements** gain **Reach +1**."}, {"title": "High Chancery", "url": "wonders-ref.html", "text": "High Chancery wonder Once per turn: automatically **Condemn** or **Endorse** one Envoy Sent by any other player regardless of **Net Influence** after Influence has been spent, even if it\u2019s a Council Envoy."}, {"title": "Move", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Move Prowess action Move an Army up to its Speed in Territories, then choose: March (move up to 2x Speed, \u22121 Endurance, no other action), Skirmish (end adjacent to a non-allied Army not in a settlement \u2192 Battle, Seize the Initiative +1I Skirmish 1), Lay Siege (end adjacent to an at-war settlement \u2192 Siege), or Muster (within range 3 of your settlements, not within range 1 of a non-ally, with an active Muster Field \u2192 recruit up to combined muster limit; may swap retinues between adjacent allied armies and change equipment)."}, {"title": "Declare War", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Declare War Prowess action Choose a non-allied player you have no NAP or active truce with. Both players are now At War. Trade Agreements between you end."}, {"title": "Demand Tribute", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Demand Tribute Prowess action Choose a non-allied player with no NAP. Negotiate: Target agrees \u2192 sign a NAP or Alliance (target's choice of offered terms); Target refuses or fails terms \u2192 immediately Declare War on them."}, {"title": "Intercept Caravan", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Intercept Caravan Cunning action Choose a player. The next turn they are Host, Extort their Trade Income."}, {"title": "Foster Rebellion", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Foster Rebellion Cunning action Choose a player. At the next Bandit Mechanic Phase, place a Bandit Camp with 10 retinues in their Outlaw Country."}, {"title": "Raze", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Raze Cunning action Choose another player's settlement. Select one active Pursuit, active Infrastructure, or active Build Timer there \u2014 it becomes Damaged; its effects are inactive until Repaired. A damaged Build Timer does not increment until Repaired."}, {"title": "Destabilize", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Destabilize Cunning action Choose a player. Extort their Tax Income at the beginning of next turn."}, {"title": "Spread Gospel", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Spread Gospel Piety action All non-allied players gain Doubt 1. All allied players gain Faith 1."}, {"title": "Send Missionaries", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Send Missionaries Piety action Choose a target player or alliance. Outside your alliance \u2192 all players in the target alliance gain Doubt 2. Inside your alliance \u2192 all other allied players gain Faith 2."}, {"title": "Tithe", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Tithe Piety action Choose a player. Extort 10% of their treasury (round down to nearest 100, min 0)."}, {"title": "Convert", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Convert Piety action Choose another player's closest non-capital settlement; they must have Public Order \u22125 or lower. Lay Siege using only settlement-type siege modifiers (Wooden Walls, Stone Walls, Citadel, Garrison, Standing Army) and set a Convert Timer. At 0, the settlement joins your empire (see Capture)."}, {"title": "Crusade", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Crusade Piety action Declare War on a non-ally with no NAP or truce, then immediately perform a Move action with one of your armies."}, {"title": "Build", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Build Industry action Choose an unlocked, available Infrastructure; set a Build Timer equal to its build time. On completion it becomes active in all settlements in your province."}, {"title": "Repair", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Repair Industry action Choose a damaged Pursuit or Infrastructure in a settlement you control; set Repair Timer 2. At 0, choose: Restore (reactivate with all effects) or Demolish (remove it, freeing the ward)."}, {"title": "Pursue", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Pursue Industry action Choose an inactive settlement ward you control. Select a Pursuit whose prerequisites you meet; set a Build Timer equal to its build time (usually 1). On completion, place the Pursuit; innate effects activate immediately, mastery if all mastery reqs met."}, {"title": "Charter", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Charter Industry action Choose: Charter a new Village (uncontrolled or in-province non-water/mountain territory, range 4+ from any settlement, not within range 2 of Outlaw Country); Charter a Hamlet (if none, range 2 from capital, non-water/mountain \u2014 a Hamlet always allows pursuing Arable Land even if that raw material is not in its region); or Expand an existing non-city settlement by one tier into an adjacent territory (Village \u2192 Sea/Town, Sea/Town \u2192 Port/City, Port/City \u2192 Metropolis), adding a ward."}, {"title": "Sign Treaty", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Sign Treaty Diplomacy action Ask players to agree; choose one and both sign one of: Peace Treaty (end war, truce timer 5), Trade Agreement (begin trading next turn), Non-Aggression Pact (no Declare War; ending it via End Treaty gives both truce timer 5), or Alliance (join/form/invite to Defensive or Military Alliance)."}, {"title": "Negotiate", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "Negotiate Diplomacy action Propose terms to a target; they agree or refuse. Terms may include gold, settlement ownership, territory, treaty sign/end, or promises (non-binding)."}, {"title": "End Treaty", "url": "actions-ref.html", "text": "End Treaty Diplomacy action Choose a target with an active treaty signed with you; that treaty is removed. Does not require the target to agree."}, {"title": "Envoy Outcomes", "url": "envoy-outcomes-ref.html", "text": "envoy outcomes condemned failed passed endorsed net influence resolve domain"}, {"title": "Peace Treaty", "url": "treaties-ref.html", "text": "Peace Treaty treaty Ends war between the two players; sets Truce Timer 5."}, {"title": "Trade Agreement", "url": "treaties-ref.html", "text": "Trade Agreement treaty Begin trading (Trade Income flows from next turn). Requires bordering + active Dirt Road."}, {"title": "Non-Aggression Pact", "url": "treaties-ref.html", "text": "Non-Aggression Pact treaty Neither player may Declare War on the other. Ending it via End Treaty gives both a Truce Timer 5."}, {"title": "Military Alliance", "url": "treaties-ref.html", "text": "Military Alliance treaty Mutual offensive pact: if a member Declares War, all members Declare War on the target next turn (and send 1 fewer envoy)."}, {"title": "Defensive Alliance", "url": "treaties-ref.html", "text": "Defensive Alliance treaty Mutual defense: attacking one member puts all members at war with the attacker."}, {"title": "Sovereign Standing", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Sovereign Standing edict win Reach a Sovereign Standing (Domain value 10) in any Domain."}, {"title": "Monument", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Monument edict win Complete (build) a Monument pursuit."}, {"title": "Wonder", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Wonder edict win Complete a World Wonder."}, {"title": "Wealth", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Wealth edict win Generate 10,000 gold per turn for five consecutive turns."}, {"title": "Vassalize", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Vassalize edict win Vassalize a rival player (control their capital with no other settlements/armies under them)."}, {"title": "Living Saints", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Living Saints edict win Sustain Public Order 10 (Living Saints) for five consecutive turns (Pious Timer)."}, {"title": "Last Alliance Standing", "url": "edicts-ref.html", "text": "Last Alliance Standing edict win Be the last alliance standing \u2014 the game-ending stop condition."}, {"title": "Economy Reference", "url": "economy-ref.html", "text": "upkeep costs pursuit army infrastructure tax trade 2000 gold (the envoy action; pursuit then costs per-turn upkeep by type) Per turn by type (fixed): Monument 300, Power 200, Energy 0, all others 100 retinue count x (retinue cost - Upkeep -X modifiers) Per-settlement (see INFRASTRUCTURE); Trade Guild removes Primitive/Developed, College of Engineering removes Sophisticated 2000 gold (Intercept Caravan / Foster Rebellion / Raze / Destabilize) 2000 gold (Build / Repair / Pursue / Charter) Doubt 1 (Spread Gospel / Send Missionaries / Tithe / Convert / Crusade) None (Move / Declare War / Demand Tribute) None (Sign Treaty / Negotiate / End Treaty) Extort 1000 per settlement tier; reduce settlement by 1 tier; Sack Timer 2 500 gold per settlement tier per turn (collected in Winter) 100 x host's Craft X per active Trade Agreement"}, {"title": "Grassland", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Grassland terrain \u2014"}, {"title": "Wetlands", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Wetlands terrain Speed -1"}, {"title": "Tundra", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Tundra terrain gain Strained"}, {"title": "Mountains", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Mountains terrain Impassable"}, {"title": "Water", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Water terrain Must end move after passing over 1 Water Territory (must end on land)"}, {"title": "Forest", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Forest terrain Speed -1"}, {"title": "Hill", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "Hill terrain Gains Seize the Initiative. Where Settlements can be chartered."}, {"title": "Terrain & Movement", "url": "terrain-ref.html", "text": "terrain movement grassland wetland tundra mountain water forest roads bridge"}, {"title": "Bandits", "url": "bandits-ref.html", "text": "bandits outlaw country camp army growth cunning raze destabilize"}, {"title": "Timers, Influence & PO", "url": "systems-ref.html", "text": "timers influence public order modifiers faith doubt border tension"}, {"title": "Settlements", "url": "settlements-ref.html", "text": "settlements hamlet village town city metropolis tax muster wards reach"}, {"title": "Eras", "url": "eras-ref.html", "text": "eras founding ascension eminence zenith renown army cap"}, {"title": "Public Order Track", "url": "public-order-ref.html", "text": "public order faith doubt uprising living saints"}, {"title": "Domain Board", "url": "domain-board-ref.html", "text": "domain board standing indomitable grand vizier influence"}, {"title": "Seasons", "url": "seasons-ref.html", "text": "seasons winter spring summer fall"}, {"title": "Equipment", "url": "equipment-ref.html", "text": "equipment retinues weapons ranged shields armor stats"}, {"title": "Reference Tables", "url": "reference-tables.html", "text": "bandits timers influence gain trade rules build timers tier unlock standing effects"}, {"title": "Tactic Matrix", "url": "tactic-matrix-ref.html", "text": "tactic matrix scout ambush flank charge fighting defensive formation fall back initiative"}, {"title": "Escalation Campaign", "url": "escalation.html", "text": "escalation campaign combat battle mode overview"}, {"title": "Escalation Battle Rules", "url": "escalation-rules.html", "text": "escalation battle rules setup turn sequence skirmish walkthrough victory points dice"}, {"title": "Escalation Combat Pursuits", "url": "escalation-pursuits.html", "text": "escalation combat pursuits industry prowess piety cunning ranks mastery monument"}, {"title": "Combat Keywords", "url": "keywords-ref.html", "text": "keywords deadly cleave poison parry riposte"}, {"title": "Steady", "url": "glossary.html#steady", "text": "Steady Initiative cannot be reduced by Tactics."}, {"title": "Unwieldy", "url": "glossary.html#unwieldy", "text": "Unwieldy Initiative cannot be improved by Tactics."}, {"title": "2H", "url": "glossary.html#2h", "text": "2H Cannot use a Shield."}, {"title": "Deadly", "url": "glossary.html#deadly", "text": "Deadly On a Focused Strike: increase AP by -5, and the defender may Parry or Recover only with a Focused roll."}, {"title": "Unstoppable", "url": "glossary.html#unstoppable", "text": "Unstoppable Parried only by a Focused roll."}, {"title": "Cleave", "url": "glossary.html#cleave", "text": "Cleave On a Focused Strike: roll one extra Strike die at your modified to-Strike."}, {"title": "Poison", "url": "glossary.html#poison", "text": "Poison When the Defender receives a Strike and rolls a Focused Save, it fails; the resulting wound may only be Recovered with a Focused Recover."}, {"title": "Nimble", "url": "glossary.html#nimble", "text": "Nimble Gain +1 Initiative in the first Skirmish of each Battle."}, {"title": "Drilled", "url": "glossary.html#drilled", "text": "Drilled Does not lose Endurance in the first Skirmish of each Battle."}, {"title": "Destroy Shield", "url": "glossary.html#destroy-shield", "text": "Destroy Shield On a Focused Strike: the target loses its Shield attributes for the rest of the Battle."}, {"title": "Blunder", "url": "glossary.html#blunder", "text": "Blunder At Initiative -2 or lower, your to-Strike is set to 6+, before other negative modifiers."}, {"title": "One Shot", "url": "glossary.html#one-shot", "text": "One Shot May only be Equipped in the first Skirmish of a Battle. Requires a Tiltyard."}, {"title": "Parry", "url": "glossary.html#parry", "text": "Parry While not Fatigued, roll a d6 to attempt to Parry a Strike before the Save. On a 5+, the Strike is Parried."}, {"title": "Riposte", "url": "glossary.html#riposte", "text": "Riposte While not Fatigued, if you Focused a Parry against a Melee Weapon's Strike, you Riposte: your opponent immediately takes a Strike from your melee weapon. You can Riposte a Riposte."}, {"title": "Recover", "url": "glossary.html#recover", "text": "Recover While not Fatigued, if a to-Save roll fails, roll a d6: a result of X+ Recovers the retinue."}, {"title": "Serrated", "url": "glossary.html#serrated", "text": "Serrated -2 to Recover against this weapon's Strikes (worsens the defender's Recover roll by 2)."}, {"title": "Tempered", "url": "glossary.html#tempered", "text": "Tempered A Focused Save succeeds, regardless of AP."}, {"title": "Fatigue Token", "url": "glossary.html#fatigue-token", "text": "Fatigue Token Each token is -1 to your Strike to a maximum of 6+; and Morale -1 (uncapped). If your modified Morale is ever 7+, your army Routs. Tokens stack."}, {"title": "Shielded", "url": "glossary.html#shielded", "text": "Shielded A stacking -1 penalty to the Strike roll (to a maximum of 6+). Sources: a shield's -1 to Strike."}, {"title": "Negate Tempered", "url": "glossary.html#negate-tempered", "text": "Negate Tempered Ignores Tempered: this weapon's AP can reduce the target's Save past 6+ (to auto-fail), defeating the Tempered floor."}, {"title": "Negate Riposte", "url": "glossary.html#negate-riposte", "text": "Negate Riposte The target's Parry can never Riposte this weapon's Strikes (a natural 6 Parry still cancels the Strike, but no counter-Strike follows)."}, {"title": "Dual Wield", "url": "glossary.html#dual-wield", "text": "Dual Wield A Strike die that fails to Strike is rerolled once; the reroll can Focused Strike. Dual Wield confers 2H (both hands on weapons \u2014 no Shield). You cannot reroll successful Strikes."}, {"title": "Florentine", "url": "glossary.html#florentine", "text": "Florentine Only active while Dual Wielding. Even while Fatigued, a Focused Parry succeeds. This alone does not enable Riposte while Fatigued."}, {"title": "Immune [keyword]", "url": "glossary.html#immune-keyword", "text": "Immune [keyword] Cancels that keyword as it applies to you (e.g. Immune Unwieldy, Strain, Destroy Shield)."}, {"title": "AP", "url": "glossary.html#ap", "text": "AP Armor Penetration \u2014 a weapon's (negative) modifier to the defender's Save roll; the more negative, the harder to save."}, {"title": "Blocked", "url": "glossary.html#blocked", "text": "Blocked -1 Initiative in the first Skirmish (negated by Immune Blocked)."}, {"title": "Strained", "url": "glossary.html#strained", "text": "Strained -1 Initiative every Skirmish (negated by Immune Strain). Does not gain Endurance in the Empire Phase."}, {"title": "Seize the Initiative", "url": "glossary.html#seize-the-initiative", "text": "Seize the Initiative Won by the roll-off at the start of the Battle \u2014 the winner of their last Battle adds +1 to the roll. You become the Attacker and gain +1 Initiative in the first Skirmish. Some Tactics and the Ministry monument also grant it."}, {"title": "Attacker / Defender", "url": "glossary.html#attacker-defender", "text": "Attacker / Defender Set by the roll-off. Each Skirmish the Attacker declares equipment first; the Defender then responds."}, {"title": "Battle", "url": "glossary.html#battle", "text": "Battle One fight between two players, resolved as a series of Skirmishes until a side is wiped out, Routs, or Falls Back."}, {"title": "Skirmish", "url": "glossary.html#skirmish", "text": "Skirmish One round of a Battle, run through the numbered Battle steps; a Battle repeats Skirmishes until it ends."}, {"title": "Casualty", "url": "glossary.html#casualty", "text": "Casualty A retinue removed from the field \u2014 from an unsaved Strike or a failed Panic or Break check."}, {"title": "Field", "url": "glossary.html#field", "text": "Field Your retinues in play \u2014 front line (up to 10) plus reserve (up to 5). Casualties leave the field at once, lowering its count."}, {"title": "Endurance", "url": "glossary.html#endurance", "text": "Endurance A side's stamina. Each side that fights loses 1 per Skirmish; at 0 it becomes Fatigued."}, {"title": "Fatigued", "url": "glossary.html#fatigued", "text": "Fatigued A side at 0 Endurance. Each Skirmish its field takes a Break check, then it gains a Fatigue token. Fatigued Armies cannot Parry, Riposte, or Recover"}, {"title": "Break check", "url": "glossary.html#break-check", "text": "Break check Taken by each Fatigued side's field every Skirmish, just before it gains its Fatigue token. Roll Morale (up to 5 dice, modified by Fatigue tokens); failures are casualties, but a Break check never triggers a Panic check. Unbreakable auto-passes."}, {"title": "Panic check", "url": "glossary.html#panic-check", "text": "Panic check Taken at most once per Skirmish by a side that suffered more than 5 casualties in that Skirmish, after it Strikes back. Roll Morale (up to 5 dice); Immune Panic auto-passes."}, {"title": "Morale", "url": "glossary.html#morale", "text": "Morale How steady a retinue is when tested (lower is steadier; see the retinue table). Break and Panic checks roll it: a D6 per retinue in the field, up to 5 dice, each must meet its modified value; failures are casualties. If the modified value is ever 7+, the army Routs."}, {"title": "Rout", "url": "glossary.html#rout", "text": "Rout The army breaks and leaves the Battle (you lose it). Whenever an army's modified Morale value reaches 7 or more, it Routs automatically."}, {"title": "Fall Back", "url": "glossary.html#fall-back", "text": "Fall Back A controlled retreat that ends the Battle with at least one retinue left \u2014 a partial success."}, {"title": "Strike", "url": "glossary.html#strike", "text": "Strike A landed hit. Roll a D6, apply modifiers to the roll, and Strike on a result >= the to-Strike number. The target may then Parry, Save, and Recover."}, {"title": "to-Strike number", "url": "glossary.html#to-strike-number", "text": "to-Strike number The D6 result a retinue needs to Strike (see the retinue table; lower is better). Bonuses add to the roll; penalties and Fatigue tokens subtract."}, {"title": "Save", "url": "glossary.html#save", "text": "Save The defender's roll to avoid a casualty: roll a D6, add the weapon's AP (a negative) and the shield's Save bonus (a positive); the hit is saved on a result >= the armor value."}, {"title": "Natural roll", "url": "glossary.html#natural-roll", "text": "Natural roll The number on the die before any modifiers. Modifiers never change what counts as 'natural'."}, {"title": "Initiative", "url": "glossary.html#initiative", "text": "Initiative Decides who Strikes first each Skirmish (higher first). Runs -2 to +2 (Ministry can raise the maximum to +3). At -2 or lower you Blunder."}, {"title": "Tactic", "url": "glossary.html#tactic", "text": "Tactic A choice both players make secretly and reveal together each Skirmish; it can shift Initiative, Strike, and Save rolls."}, {"title": "Dual-equip", "url": "glossary.html#dual-equip", "text": "Dual-equip Carry two weapons at once (e.g. melee + ranged). Granted by the Tiltyard, which also gives Unwieldy until its mastery removes it."}, {"title": "Edict", "url": "glossary.html#edict", "text": "Edict A scoring achievement / win path: reach a Sovereign Standing, complete a Monument, or fulfill a victory condition (Wonder, wealth, Vassalize, Living Saints, Last Standing)."}, {"title": "Monument", "url": "glossary.html#monument", "text": "Monument A Domain's capstone Pursuit. Completing one scores its Edict and grants a powerful effect."}, {"title": "Faith X", "url": "glossary.html#faith-x", "text": "Faith X Gain X Faith: each Faith raises your Public Order track by 1 when resolved."}, {"title": "Doubt X", "url": "glossary.html#doubt-x", "text": "Doubt X Gain X Doubt: each Doubt lowers your Public Order track by 1 when resolved."}, {"title": "Extort X", "url": "glossary.html#extort-x", "text": "Extort X Take X from the stated source: the gold goes to you instead of its owner."}, {"title": "Recoup", "url": "glossary.html#recoup", "text": "Recoup Regain the stated cost in gold after paying it."}, {"title": "Speed", "url": "glossary.html#speed", "text": "Speed An Army's movement allowance in Territories per Move action. Base Speed value of an army is Speed 2"}, {"title": "Influence", "url": "glossary.html#influence", "text": "Influence The political currency of voting. Spend it to Support or Oppose Envoys. You gain it each turn from your Era, innate modifiers (trade partners, alliances, war), Pursuits, and Infrastructure."}, {"title": "Influence X", "url": "glossary.html#influence-x", "text": "Influence X An automatic +X (or -X) to an Envoy's net Influence from a Pursuit, Infrastructure, or Faction."}, {"title": "Envoy", "url": "glossary.html#envoy", "text": "Envoy The currency of actions: send an Envoy to perform an action during the Envoy Phase. Council Envoys act on the voted Domain; Personal Envoys are sent by Era progression."}, {"title": "Vote", "url": "glossary.html#vote", "text": "Vote On each Envoy, every player in clockwise order from the starting player must Support, Oppose, or Abstain."}, {"title": "Support X", "url": "glossary.html#support-x", "text": "Support X Spend X Influence to increase an Envoy's net Influence."}, {"title": "Oppose X", "url": "glossary.html#oppose-x", "text": "Oppose X Spend X Influence to decrease an Envoy's net Influence."}, {"title": "Abstain", "url": "glossary.html#abstain", "text": "Abstain Decline to spend Influence on a vote."}, {"title": "Net Influence", "url": "glossary.html#net-influence", "text": "Net Influence The sum of an Envoy's starting Influence (1+ by Standing) and all Support, Oppose, and Influence X. The total sets the outcome: -3 or less Condemned, 0 or less Failed (gain Doubt +1), 1+ passes."}, {"title": "Endorsed", "url": "glossary.html#endorsed", "text": "Endorsed An Envoy that passes with 3+ net Influence, triggering its endorsed effect (and a Domain's Rising/Established/Sovereign endorsement)."}, {"title": "Condemned", "url": "glossary.html#condemned", "text": "Condemned An Envoy whose net Influence is -3 or less: it fails and you resolve that Domain's Condemn effect."}, {"title": "Council Phase", "url": "glossary.html#council-phase", "text": "Council Phase Before Personal Envoys, all players vote on a Domain (clockwise; Host breaks ties). Each then sends a free Council Envoy of that Domain. Council Envoys auto-Abstain and their net Influence cannot drop below 1."}, {"title": "Council Envoy", "url": "glossary.html#council-envoy", "text": "Council Envoy A free Envoy resolved in the Council Phase on the voted Domain; auto-Abstained, net Influence floored at 1."}, {"title": "Personal Envoy", "url": "glossary.html#personal-envoy", "text": "Personal Envoy An Envoy you send in the Envoy Phase to perform an action; count and reach scale with Era."}, {"title": "Envoy Outcome", "url": "glossary.html#envoy-outcome", "text": "Envoy Outcome How a Sent Envoy resolves, by Net Influence: Condemned (<= -3), Failed (-3 < Net <= 0, gain Doubt 1), Passed (>= 1), Endorsed (>= 3). The per-domain effect at each band is given by ENVOY_OUTCOMES; an action's own endorsed bonus overrides the domain default."}, {"title": "Charter", "url": "glossary.html#charter", "text": "Charter Found or upgrade a Settlement (Industry action)."}, {"title": "Muster", "url": "glossary.html#muster", "text": "Muster Raise retinues into an Army, up to a Settlement's muster limit (Industry/Prowess)."}, {"title": "Pursue", "url": "glossary.html#pursue", "text": "Pursue Build a Pursuit, spending its purchase cost and a Settlement ward (Industry)."}, {"title": "Build", "url": "glossary.html#build", "text": "Build Construct Infrastructure (Industry action)."}, {"title": "Repair", "url": "glossary.html#repair", "text": "Repair Restore damaged Infrastructure or Settlements (Industry)."}, {"title": "Move", "url": "glossary.html#move", "text": "Move Advance an Army up to its Speed in Territories (Prowess)."}, {"title": "Demand Tribute", "url": "glossary.html#demand-tribute", "text": "Demand Tribute Coerce gold or concessions from another player (Prowess)."}, {"title": "Diplomacy", "url": "glossary.html#diplomacy", "text": "Diplomacy Free Envoy actions for forming and ending Treaties and Trade Agreements; resolved before Domain Envoys."}, {"title": "Treaty", "url": "glossary.html#treaty", "text": "Treaty A standing agreement between players (e.g. Trade Agreement, Non-Aggression, Alliance) signed via Diplomacy."}, {"title": "Alliance", "url": "glossary.html#alliance", "text": "Alliance A Treaty binding players to mutual support; Military and Defensive Alliances unlock by Era."}, {"title": "Vassal", "url": "glossary.html#vassal", "text": "Vassal A player subordinated via Vassalization: their chartered settlements return to them, they mirror the Suzerain's Treaties, count as allied to the Suzerain, and cannot perform or be targeted by Diplomacy actions."}, {"title": "Suzerain", "url": "glossary.html#suzerain", "text": "Suzerain The player who has Vassalized another; the vassal mirrors their Treaties."}, {"title": "Renown", "url": "glossary.html#renown", "text": "Renown The shared progress track. Gain 1 per Rest Phase; thresholds raise your Era (Ascension 8, Eminence 18, Zenith 30)."}, {"title": "Domain", "url": "glossary.html#domain", "text": "Domain One of the four identities \u2014 Industry, Prowess, Cunning, Piety \u2014 raised by spending Domain points. Values 3/6/10 = Rising/Established/Sovereign Standing."}, {"title": "Domain Point", "url": "glossary.html#domain-point", "text": "Domain Point Gained 1 per Rest Phase; spend to raise a Domain value by 1."}, {"title": "Standing", "url": "glossary.html#standing", "text": "Standing Your tier in a Domain: Untested, Rising (3), Established (6), Sovereign (10). Sets max Influence per vote (1/2/3/4) and unlocks Domain effects."}, {"title": "Public Order", "url": "glossary.html#public-order", "text": "Public Order A track from -5 to 10, adjusted each turn by Faith minus Doubt; its band applies cumulative effects (see the Public Order table)."}, {"title": "Reach", "url": "glossary.html#reach", "text": "Reach How far a Settlement projects control, in Territories (by tier). Calculated like Range X"}, {"title": "Bandit", "url": "glossary.html#bandit", "text": "Bandit Neutral hostile force; Bandit Camps spawn in Outlaw Country and on low Public Order."}, {"title": "Outlaw Country", "url": "glossary.html#outlaw-country", "text": "Outlaw Country Uncontrollable territories in your starting region where Bandit Camps spawn, starting at 3 and expanding if there is no room to place new Bandit Camps."}, {"title": "Siege", "url": "glossary.html#siege", "text": "Siege Sieging a Settlement with an Army to capture it; does not increment in Winter."}, {"title": "Border", "url": "glossary.html#border", "text": "Border Your Settlement's Reach is Range 1 or within Reach of another Player's Reach."}, {"title": "Province", "url": "glossary.html#province", "text": "Province The collection of Contested Territory and Controlled Territory by your Settlement's Reach."}, {"title": "Region", "url": "glossary.html#region", "text": "Region A collection of Territories of the same Type."}, {"title": "Realm", "url": "glossary.html#realm", "text": "Realm The total collection of Regions."}, {"title": "Territory", "url": "glossary.html#territory", "text": "Territory 1 Hex."}, {"title": "Contested", "url": "glossary.html#contested", "text": "Contested Territory that is within Reach of more than one player's settlement(s). Considered Controlled by all Players that have a Settlement within Reach."}, {"title": "Controlled", "url": "glossary.html#controlled", "text": "Controlled Territory that is within Reach of a single Player's Settlement(s)."}, {"title": "Uncontrolled", "url": "glossary.html#uncontrolled", "text": "Uncontrolled Territory that is not within Reach of any Player Settlement."}, {"title": "adjacent", "url": "glossary.html#adjacent", "text": "adjacent Range 1."}, {"title": "next to", "url": "glossary.html#next-to", "text": "next to Range 2."}, {"title": "within", "url": "glossary.html#within", "text": "within Range 0."}, {"title": "Range X", "url": "glossary.html#range-x", "text": "Range X The amount of Territories you must move in order to get from your current position to the specific Territory."}, {"title": "Reach X", "url": "glossary.html#reach-x", "text": "Reach X The Range X characteristic which determines what Territories you Control and are in your Province."}, {"title": "Host", "url": "glossary.html#host", "text": "Host The turn's starting player, who holds the Host Card. The role passes clockwise each Rest Phase (there is no Host in Spring). The Host collects and distributes Trade Income, resolves Bandit Mechanics, and breaks ties (Council vote, bandit targeting, and any tie not otherwise resolved)."}, {"title": "Send an Envoy", "url": "glossary.html#send-an-envoy", "text": "Send an Envoy Declare a Domain, spend 1 Envoy."}, {"title": "Perform", "url": "glossary.html#perform", "text": "Perform When you Perform an action, immediately do the description of the action. Pay the action's normal Cost."}, {"title": "Resolve", "url": "glossary.html#resolve", "text": "Resolve Attempt to Perform an action."}, {"title": "Cost / Pay", "url": "glossary.html#cost-pay", "text": "Cost / Pay Cost to perform an action, usually in Gold or Doubt."}, {"title": "Fail", "url": "glossary.html#fail", "text": "Fail An unsuccessful to Hit or to Save."}, {"title": "Failed", "url": "glossary.html#failed", "text": "Failed Net Influence 0 or less."}, {"title": "Passed", "url": "glossary.html#passed", "text": "Passed Net Influence 1 or more."}];const q=document.getElementById('q'),box=document.getElementById('results');let sel=-1,cur=[];
q.addEventListener('input',()=>{const v=q.value.toLowerCase().trim();sel=-1;if(v.length<2){box.style.display='none';return;}
cur=IDX.map(d=>{const t=d.title.toLowerCase(),x=d.text.toLowerCase();let s=0;if(t===v)s=100;else if(t.startsWith(v))s=60;else if(t.includes(v))s=40;else if(x.includes(v))s=15;return{d,s};}).filter(o=>o.s>0).sort((a,b)=>b.s-a.s).slice(0,14);
if(!cur.length){box.innerHTML='<a><span class=s>No matches</span></a>';box.style.display='block';return;}
box.innerHTML=cur.map((o,i)=>`<a href="${o.d.url}" data-i="${i}"><span class="t">${o.d.title}</span> <span class="s">${o.d.text.slice(0,80).replace(/</g,'&lt;')}…</span></a>`).join('');box.style.display='block';});
q.addEventListener('keydown',e=>{const a=box.querySelectorAll('a');if(e.key==='ArrowDown')sel=Math.min(sel+1,a.length-1);else if(e.key==='ArrowUp')sel=Math.max(sel-1,0);else if(e.key==='Enter'&&cur.length){location.href=cur[Math.max(sel,0)].d.url;return;}else return;a.forEach((el,i)=>el.classList.toggle('sel',i===sel));e.preventDefault();});
document.addEventListener('click',e=>{if(e.target!==q)box.style.display='none';});